Year = {2025},
Volume = {79},
Number = {1},
Pages = {91-101},
Month = {JAN 2},
Abstract = {Despite the fact that most police departments in the U.S. serve
   jurisdictions with fewer than 10,000 residents, policing practices in
   small towns are understudied. This is due in part to data limitations
   and technological barriers that exist in the small-town context. In this
   article we focus on one small town police department in New England with
   a history of misconduct, and develop a comprehensive data science
   pipeline that addresses the stages from design and collection to
   reporting. We present the reader with specific tools in the open-source
   Python ecosystem for replicating this pipeline. Once these data are
   processed, we perform two statistical analyses in an attempt to better
   understand the provisions of service by the small-town police department
   of focus. First, we perform ecological inference to estimate the rate at
   which residents are placing calls for service. Second, we model wait
   times using a negative binomal regression model to account for
   overdispersion in the data. We discuss data and model limitations
   arising through the pipeline creation and analysis process.},
