Note = {20th International Conference on Intelligent Computer Communication and
   Processing, Cluj-Napoca, ROMANIA, OCT 17-19, 2024},
Abstract = {Detecting deception through automated tools involves computational
   techniques to identify falsehoods in text, which is crucial for
   evaluating the truthfulness of testimonies in the legal field. The
   present research explores deception detection in Romanian texts using
   various methods. Initially, ANNs with different text representations,
   such as TF-IDF, LSA, and LIWC features were employed. These approaches
   were compared with BERT-based models on augmented data, assessing
   improvements in classification performance. Additionally, CNNs with
   embedding representations were used to examine the impact of context on
   detection accuracy. To gain deeper insights, LIME (Local Interpretable
   Model-agnostic Explanations) was applied to visualise the importance of
   specific words and phrases in court statements. The present work is
   particularly novel for Romanian, as research on textual perjury
   detection in this language is limited. The obtained results are
   competitive with existing literature, highlighting the potential of the
   proposed approaches and impacting the fields of forensic linguistics and
   natural language processing, especially given the lack of research in
   non-English languages.},
