   JAPAN, NOV 13-15, 2021},
Abstract = {Drunk driving cases often arouse public concern in Taiwanese society.
   According to 2013 amended Paragraph 1 of Article 185-3, the Taiwan
   Criminal Code, a drunk person may face up to a maximum sentence of two
   years in prison if his/her exhalation contains alcohol of 0.25 mg per
   liter or more, or blood alcohol concentration is 0.05\% or more. The
   huge volume of ``drunk driving{''} cases becomes a considerable workload
   for the court and therefore it may be worthwhile developing an automatic
   sentencing supportive system. This research attempts to train a
   deep-learning model to predict sentences by inputting the section of
   ``recidivist/facts of the judgement.{''} The TextCNN (Convolutional
   Neural Networks) model reached a 73\% accuracy rate in four-category
   sentencing prediction. This research suggests that adopting two kinds of
   pre-processing methods and a well-trained model directly to unstructured
   judgement texts without word segmentation can result in a good
   performance. It opens the possibility of applying different machine
   learning techniques to legal texts.},
