Abstract = {Estonia has successfully created a digital society within the past 2
   decades. It is best known for its eGovernment achievements, but it is
   also home for four unicorn star-ups. While the state is aiming to
   attract tech investments with e-Residency program and has recently
   started to invest into protecting national IP and safeguarding data from
   cybercrime by applying blockchain technology and creating its ``digital
   embassy{''} in Luxembourg, emerging technologies such as and
   applications of artificial intelligence but also internet of things have
   posed the question on legal regulation and standardization. The dilemma,
   however, seems to be that since the new technologies, such artificial
   intelligence is much more overwhelming phenomenon than e-governance and
   presumably, before deciding the legal standards, the political and
   economic strategies that go beyond the e-governance should be set.},
